

This project successfully developed an end-to-end Natural Language Processing (NLP) sentiment classification system capable of analysing and categorising user-generated text into Negative, Neutral, and Positive sentiment classes.

The implementation involved a complete machine learning workflow including exploratory data analysis, text preprocessing, feature extraction using TF-IDF, model training, evaluation, and performance interpretation.

The Support Vector Machine classifier achieved an overall accuracy of **79%**, demonstrating that traditional machine learning techniques can effectively perform sentiment analysis when combined with appropriate preprocessing and feature engineering.

The model performed particularly well in identifying negative and neutral sentiments, achieving F1-scores of **0.89** and **0.84** respectively. This indicates strong potential for real-world applications where detecting dissatisfaction or monitoring general customer sentiment is important.

Although positive sentiment classification showed comparatively lower performance, this provides opportunities for future improvement through:

* Larger and more balanced datasets
* Advanced natural language embeddings
* Deep learning approaches
* Hyperparameter optimisation
* Ensemble modelling techniques

Overall, this project demonstrates practical experience in applying NLP and machine learning techniques to solve real-world text classification problems and provides a strong foundation for developing more advanced AI-driven analytics solutions.
